<h4>NEWS&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="color:#949494;font-weight:400;">*|DATE:l, F j, Y|*</span></h4>

<h1>More from our day on the campaign trail with Lauren Boebert. The latest on Kent Thiry&#8217;s election overhaul attempt.</h1>

<p><strong><em>Plus:</em></strong><em> There have been hundreds of statewide ballot measures in Colorado since 1880. </em><strong><em>Kelly Maher</em></strong><em>&#8217;s new &#8220;Restoring Standards&#8221; initiative.</em></p>

<!-- BYLINE --></mj-text><mj-table><tr style="border-top:1px solid #fcd232;border-bottom:1px solid #fcd232;text-align:left;"><td style="padding: 6px;"><strong>By Jesse Paul, Sandra Fish + Brian Eason</strong><br /><a target="_blank"  target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/author/jesse-paul/?utm_source=newsletter?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" target="_blank"><em><span style="font-size:12px;">Reporter</span></em></a> | <a target="_blank"  target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/author/sandra-fish/?utm_source=newsletter?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" target="_blank"><em><span style="font-size:12px;">Data Journalist</span></em></a> | <a target="_blank"  target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/author/brian-eason/?utm_source=newsletter?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" target="_blank"><em><span style="font-size:12px;">Reporter</span></em></a></td></tr></mj-table>
<mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/boebert_franktown-0224-2.jpg?w=800" /><mj-text><p class="caption">Rep. Lauren Boebert chats with customers and staff at Franktown Firearms Shooting Center on Feb. 23. (Olivia Sun, The Colorado Sun via Report for America)</span></p>

&nbsp;<hr />&nbsp;

<p style="line-height:24px;"><span style="font-size:48px;line-height:12px;">N</span>ot everything we saw and heard during our day on the campaign trail with U.S. Rep. <strong>Lauren Boebert</strong> made <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/07/lauren-boebert-rough-year-future/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">it into our story</a> last week about the Republican congresswoman.</p>

<p>Here are some interesting details that got left on the cutting room floor:</p>

<ul><li>Speaking about Republican U.S. Rep. <strong>Ken Buck</strong>, whom Boebert is trying to replace in the 4th Congressional District, she told a voter that &#8220;he got bit by the <strong>Liz Cheney</strong> bug.&#8221; (The voter wanted to know &#8220;what happened&#8221; to Buck.)</li>

<li>Another voter asked Boebert about what she would do with the money she raised while campaigning to run for reelection in the 3rd Congressional District now that she has switched to run in the 4th District. &#8220;Not all of the donations raised came from CD3,&#8221; she said. &#8220;I am very grateful for all of the online donations that come in and all of the mail donations that come in from all across the nation. There have been many, many constituents who have donated from the 3rd, who are even <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.craigdailypress.com/news/financial-reports-show-prominent-republicans-backing-lauren-boeberts-primary-opponent/">quoted in articles</a> who say, &#8216;I'm happy for you. Keep it. If I could donate more I would.&#8217;&#8221;</li>

<li>Boebert was asked by a voter about whether Colorado&#8217;s elections are secure. &#8220;Definitely your voter rolls need to be cleaned up,&#8221; she said. &#8220;Most of those issues are state issues — that&#8217;s your secretary of state and state legislature.&#8221; Boebert said, however, the federal government shouldn&#8217;t be involved in how states run elections. She called <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/04/donald-trump-colorado-case-ruling/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">the lawsuit </a>seeking to bar Trump from appearing on Colorado&#8217;s presidential primary ballot because of his role in the Jan. 6, 2021, riot at the U.S. Capitol &#8220;election interference.&#8221;</li>

<li>Boebert said if she had continued running for reelection in the 3rd District, it may have been won by Democrats — &#8220;and that's how we got <strong>Jason Crow</strong>. They spent $20 million in that congressional election, and we're stuck with him.&#8221; Crow, a Centennial Democrat, ousted Republican U.S. Rep. <strong>Mike Coffman</strong> in Colorado&#8217;s 6th Congressional District in 2018 and he&#8217;s held the seat ever since. It was considered a toss-up district at the time and is now thought of as a firmly safe Democratic seat —both because of past election results and its makeup. The 3rd District, meanwhile, was long considered a safe Republican district— until Boebert made it a toss-up.</li>
</ul>

