<p><span style="background-color:#fcd232;"><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;MORE:&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></span> We met a handful of voters while we were out on the trail with Boebert. Here&#8217;s what some of them said about the congresswoman:</p>

<ul><li>&#8220;Everything I&#8217;ve seen with her and read about her —I just think she&#8217;s a strong force,&#8221; said <strong>Dan Stephen</strong>, who lives in Elbert County and is the manager at Franktown Firearms Shooting Center, where Boebert visited in late February. &#8220;It&#8217;s something that we need. She seems like just a very real person. It&#8217;s not really even a competition in my mind.&#8221; Stephen said he doesn&#8217;t mind that she recently moved to the district. &#8220;It&#8217;s time for change across the board,&#8221; he said. &#8220;I think that she&#8217;s going to be a very welcome change to the district.&#8221;</li>

<li><strong>Carmen Smith</strong>, a Republican voter who lives in Douglas County, attended a meet-and-greet with Boebert later in the day at a home near Franktown. She came to the event undecided on whom she would vote for in the Republican 4th District primary, but left intending to support Boebert. &#8220;Anyone who can pray like that from her heart has my vote, because I know where her focus is, I know where she goes to get help to make decisions and I know it&#8217;s from the heart,&#8221; Smith said of Boebert, nodding to the congresswoman&#8217;s long opening prayer to kick off the gathering. &#8220;It&#8217;s not some made-up political agenda.&#8221;</li>

<li>A man who attended the meet-and-greet said he was backing Boebert because of her performance at a <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/02/13/the-unaffiliated-20240213/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">Douglas County debate</a> for 4th District GOP candidate. &#8220;Everybody up on the stage was acting like a grandmother or grandpa at a church meeting, except for one person,&#8221; he said. &#8220;There was only one person up there that acted like they were ready for a street fight — like they were ready for a fistfight in Washington, D.C. And it was the tiniest person up there. It was you.&#8221;</li>
</ul>

</mj-text><mj-text margin="0" padding="0"><h3>ELECTION 2024</h3></mj-text><mj-text>

<h2>Lauren Boebert is on the primary ballot. Will she gamble her political future on the caucus and assembly route?</h2>

<p>State elections officials announced Monday that U.S. Rep. <strong>Lauren Boebert</strong> has qualified for the June 25 GOP primary ballot in the 4th District.</p>

<p>The Colorado Secretary of State&#8217;s Office said the Republican congresswoman&#8217;s reelection campaign had collected well over the 1,500 signatures from GOP voters in the district to qualify.</p>

<p>Boebert has said she will also go the caucus and assembly route to make the primary ballot. She will need the support of at least 10% of the delegates at the Republican district convention in April to stay on the ballot.</p>

<p><strong>The conundrum:</strong> If Boebert doesn&#8217;t drop her caucus and assembly bid, she is leaving her political future up to an extremely fickle process. She also runs the risk of keeping another candidate off the ballot — which may also serve to hurt her in a crowded primary she&#8217;s expected to win with only a plurality of support.</p>

<p>&#8220;If I were Boebert, I&#8217;d want to maximize the number of competitors on the primary ballot and therefore wouldn&#8217;t compete at the assembly,&#8221; <strong>Daniel Cole</strong>, a longtime Republican operative in Colorado, <a target="_blank"  href="https://twitter.com/dancoloradan/status/1767295405820412012">posted on social media</a>.</p>

<p>But if she bails on the caucus and assembly route, she runs the risk of angering a base of GOP voters who frown upon candidates who make the ballot only by gathering signatures.</p>

<p>Boebert was the first of nine Republican 4th District candidates seeking to make the ballot by gathering signatures to submit them. She&#8217;s the only one who has qualified thus far.</p>

<p>Conservative commentator<strong> Deborah Flora </strong>submitted her signatures Friday, and as of Monday afternoon was the only other Boebert primary opponent to do so.</p>

<p>Major party candidates running in all 2024 races have until Tuesday to turn in their signatures to make the primary ballot.</p>

<p><span style="background-color:#fcd232;"><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;MORE:&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></span> Weld County Councilman <strong>Trent Leisy</strong> has dropped out of the 4th District GOP primary and will run for Republican state Rep. <strong>Mike Lynch</strong>&#8217;s House Distrit 65 seat instead. (Lynch is running in the 4th District primary and vacating his statehouse seat because running for two offices at once isn&#8217;t allowed.)</p>

<p>Leisy, the self-proclaimed &#8220;MAGA king&#8221; had virtually no shot of winning the 4th District primary.</p>

<p>&#8220;I have come to believe I am best positioned to fight for rightful President Trump, the patriots of Colorado, and stand up to the radical, satanic left as the next representative for Colorado House District 65," Leisy said in a written statement.</p>

